Report on diamonds data analysis

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(readr)

Problem Statement

Understand and analyse features that effect the price of the diamonds.

Data Ingestion

This classic dataset contains the prices and other attributes of almost 54,000 diamonds. It’s a great dataset for beginners learning to work with data analysis and visualization.

Content price price in US dollars ($326–$18,823)

carat weight of the diamond (0.2–5.01)

cut quality of the cut (Fair, Good, Very Good, Premium, Ideal)

color diamond colour, from J (worst) to D (best)

clarity a measurement of how clear the diamond is (I1 (worst), SI2, SI1, VS2, VS1, VVS2, VVS1, IF (best))

x length in mm (0–10.74)

y width in mm (0–58.9)

z depth in mm (0–31.8)

depth total depth percentage = z / mean(x, y) = 2 * z / (x + y) (43–79)

table width of top of diamond relative to widest point (43–95)


diamonds <- read_csv("data/raw/diamonds.csv", 
    col_types = cols(...1 = col_skip()))

                       predictor_var = "carat",
                       target_var = "price")

`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

depth vs price


tempdf <- diamonds %>%
  filter(depth > 55 & depth < 70) %>%
  mutate(price = log1p(price))
subplot_cont_cont_vars(df = tempdf,
                       predictor_var = "depth",
                       target_var = "price")
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
